System Overview :

Define the Problem:

Need:-
Limited real-world robotics data, especially for early-generation robots.

Solution:-
Simulate robot behavior in a controlled virtual environment using the Genesis physics engine, then extract detailed data (e.g., leg movement, head rotation, speed, sensor readings).



Benefits : Genesis's speed - simulation 43 million frame per second on RTX 4090 [reduce simulation time and clients costs]

Background and Context
The Genesis physics engine, released as an open-source platform, is designed for robotics, Embodied AI, and Physical AI applications. It integrates multiple physics solvers (e.g., rigid body, MPM, SPH) into a unified framework, offering ultra-fast simulations (up to 80 times faster than competitors like Isaac Gym) and photo-realistic rendering. Its Pythonic, user-friendly API lowers barriers for robotics research, making it ideal for generating synthetic data where real-world data is scarce, especially for early-stage robots.


